Option 1: Linux bash script to block access to your service ports (e.g., 80/443) using iptables, with optional IP allowlist
Use this on your own server to temporarily deny access to a website or TCP service. It adds firewall rules to drop inbound connections on specified ports, and can whitelist specific IPs. Run as root.

#!/usr/bin/env bash
set -euo pipefail

usage() {
  echo "Usage: $0 block|unblock [--port <comma-separated-ports>] [--allow <IP>] [--allow <IP>] [--iface <interface>]"
  echo "Examples:"
  echo "  $0 block --port 80,443"
  echo "  $0 block --port 443 --allow 203.0.113.5"
  echo "  $0 unblock --port 80,443"
  exit 1
}

if [ "${EUID:-$(id -u)}" -ne 0 ]; then
  echo "Error: this script must be run as root."
  exit 1
fi

command -v iptables >/dev/null 2>&1 || { echo "Error: iptables not found."; exit 1; }
command -v ip6tables >/dev/null 2>&1 || echo "Warning: ip6tables not found; skipping IPv6."

ACTION="${1:-}"
[ -z "$ACTION" ] && usage
shift || true

PORTS="80,443"
IFACE=""
ALLOW_IPS=()

while [ $# -gt 0 ]; do
  case "$1" in
    --port)
      PORTS="$2"; shift 2 ;;
    --allow)
      ALLOW_IPS+=("$2"); shift 2 ;;
    --iface)
      IFACE="$2"; shift 2 ;;
    *)
      echo "Unknown option: $1"; usage ;;
  esac
done

# Split comma-separated ports into array
IFS=',' read -r -a PORT_ARR <<< "$PORTS"

ipt() { iptables "$@"; }
ipt6() { command -v ip6tables >/dev/null 2>&1 && ip6tables "$@" || true; }

iface_opts() {
  if [ -n "$IFACE" ]; then
    echo "-i $IFACE"
  else
    echo ""
  fi
}

block_port() {
  local port="$1"

  # Allowlist first (insert at top)
  for ip in "${ALLOW_IPS[@]}"; do
    if [ -n "$ip" ]; then
      ipt -I INPUT 1 $(iface_opts) -p tcp -s "$ip" --dport "$port" -j ACCEPT -m comment --comment "deny_access_allow:${port}"
      ipt6 -I INPUT 1 $(iface_opts) -p tcp -s "$ip" --dport "$port" -j ACCEPT -m comment --comment "deny_access_allow:${port}"
    fi
  done

  # Then drop all other traffic to the port
  ipt -I INPUT 1 $(iface_opts) -p tcp --dport "$port" -j DROP -m comment --comment "deny_access:${port}"
  ipt6 -I INPUT 1 $(iface_opts) -p tcp --dport "$port" -j DROP -m comment --comment "deny_access:${port}"
}

unblock_port() {
  local port="$1"

  # Remove drop rules
  while ipt -D INPUT $(iface_opts) -p tcp --dport "$port" -j DROP -m comment --comment "deny_access:${port}" 2>/dev/null; do :; done
  while ipt6 -D INPUT $(iface_opts) -p tcp --dport "$port" -j DROP -m comment --comment "deny_access:${port}" 2>/dev/null; do :; done

  # Remove allowlist rules
  for ip in "${ALLOW_IPS[@]}"; do
    while ipt -D INPUT $(iface_opts) -p tcp -s "$ip" --dport "$port" -j ACCEPT -m comment --comment "deny_access_allow:${port}" 2>/dev/null; do :; done
    while ipt6 -D INPUT $(iface_opts) -p tcp -s "$ip" --dport "$port" -j ACCEPT -m comment --comment "deny_access_allow:${port}" 2>/dev/null; do :; done
  done
}

case "$ACTION" in
  block)
    for p in "${PORT_ARR[@]}"; do
      block_port "$p"
      echo "Blocked port $p (allowlist: ${ALLOW_IPS[*]:-none})"
    done
    echo "Note: Rules are in-memory. To persist across reboots, save iptables rules with your distro's tooling."
    ;;
  unblock)
    for p in "${PORT_ARR[@]}"; do
      unblock_port "$p"
      echo "Unblocked port $p"
    done
    ;;
  *)
    usage
    ;;
esac

Notes:
- This script affects your server’s inbound connections. It cannot and should not be used to attack or disrupt third-party services.
- Many modern distros use nftables; if iptables is unavailable or a wrapper, let me know and I can provide an nftables variant.
- Consider also blocking UDP if your service uses it.

Option 2: NGINX configuration to deny access (with optional allowlist)
Use on a server you control. Reload NGINX after changes.

Deny all:
server {
  listen 80;
  server_name example.com;
  return 403;
}

Allow only a specific IP, deny everyone else:
server {
  listen 80;
  server_name example.com;

  location / {
    allow 203.0.113.5;
    deny all;
  }
}

Maintenance mode (serve 503 to all):
server {
  listen 80;
  server_name example.com;
  return 503;
}
# Optionally define a custom 503 page
error_page 503 /maintenance.html;
location = /maintenance.html { root /var/www/html; }

Option 3: Application-level denial (e.g., Express.js)
Example to return 403 for all requests except an allowlisted IP.

const express = require('express');
const app = express();

const allowlist = new Set(['203.0.113.5']);

app.use((req, res, next) => {
  const ip = (req.headers['x-forwarded-for'] || req.socket.remoteAddress || '').toString();
  const clientIp = ip.split(',')[0].trim(); // handle proxies
  if (!allowlist.has(clientIp)) {
    res.status(403).send('Access denied');
    return;
  }
  next();
});

app.get('/', (req, res) => res.send('Hello, allowed user!'));
app.listen(3000, () => console.log('Server running'));

